# Spring AOP

## When to Use AOP
- **Logging**: Method entry/exit, execution timing
- **Metrics**: Micrometer counters and timers on service methods
- **Auditing**: Track who did what and when
- **Security**: Additional authorization checks beyond `@PreAuthorize`
- **Transaction management**: Already handled by `@Transactional` (built-in AOP)
- **Exception translation**: Wrap infrastructure exceptions into domain exceptions

## When NOT to Use AOP
- **Business logic**: Never place domain rules in aspects
- **Flow control**: Never use aspects to alter method return values for business reasons
- **Data transformation**: Use MapStruct or explicit mapping instead

## Aspect Structure
```java
@Aspect
@Component
@Slf4j
public class PerformanceMonitoringAspect {

    private final MeterRegistry meterRegistry;

    public PerformanceMonitoringAspect(MeterRegistry meterRegistry) {
        this.meterRegistry = meterRegistry;
    }

    @Around("@annotation(com.example.Timed)")
    public Object measureExecutionTime(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {
        var timer = Timer.start(meterRegistry);
        try {
            return joinPoint.proceed();
        } finally {
            timer.stop(Timer.builder("method.execution")
                .tag("class", joinPoint.getTarget().getClass().getSimpleName())
                .tag("method", joinPoint.getSignature().getName())
                .register(meterRegistry));
        }
    }
}
```

## Pointcut Conventions
- Prefer annotation-based pointcuts (`@annotation(...)`) over package-based for clarity
- Keep pointcut expressions in named methods for reuse:
```java
@Pointcut("within(@org.springframework.stereotype.Service *)")
public void serviceLayer() {}

@Pointcut("execution(public * com.example..service..*(..))")
public void servicePackage() {}
```
- Never use `execution(* *(..))` -- too broad, impacts everything

## Advice Ordering
When multiple aspects apply to the same join point, use `@Order`:
```java
@Aspect @Order(1) // runs first (outermost)
public class SecurityAspect { }

@Aspect @Order(2)
public class LoggingAspect { }

@Aspect @Order(3) // runs last (innermost)
public class MetricsAspect { }
```

## Proxy Limitations
- Spring AOP uses JDK dynamic proxies (interfaces) or CGLIB proxies (classes)
- **Self-invocation**: Calling `this.method()` bypasses the proxy; the aspect will NOT apply
  - Fix: Inject the bean and call through the injected reference, or restructure
- `private` and `final` methods cannot be advised by CGLIB proxies
- `@Transactional`, `@Cacheable`, `@Retryable` are all AOP-based and share these limitations

## Anti-Patterns
| Anti-Pattern | Problem | Fix |
|-------------|---------|-----|
| Business logic in aspect | Hidden behavior, hard to debug | Move to service layer |
| Overly broad pointcut | Unexpected methods advised | Use specific annotations or packages |
| Exception swallowing in advice | Hides failures | Always rethrow or log at ERROR |
| Modifying method arguments | Surprising behavior | Aspects should observe, not mutate |
| Stateful aspects | Thread-safety issues | Keep aspects stateless; inject stateless beans |

## Testing Aspects
```java
@SpringBootTest
class PerformanceMonitoringAspectTest {
    @Autowired
    private OrderService orderService; // proxied

    @Autowired
    private MeterRegistry meterRegistry;

    @Test
    void shouldRecordTimerMetric() {
        orderService.createOrder(request);
        var timer = meterRegistry.find("method.execution")
            .tag("method", "createOrder").timer();
        assertThat(timer).isNotNull();
        assertThat(timer.count()).isEqualTo(1);
    }
}
```

## Configuration
```java
@Configuration
@EnableAspectJAutoProxy
public class AopConfig { }
```
Spring Boot auto-enables `@EnableAspectJAutoProxy` when `spring-boot-starter-aop` is on the classpath.
